[A model of ecological hazard and social tension for the description of the 
health deterioration risk in the Russian population].

[Article in Russian]

Shafirkin AV.

A model for quantitative evaluation of risks from long-exposure to 
high-intensity anthropogenic factors and chronic psychoemotional stress is 
presented. The model has been based on the concept of G. Seliet concerning the 
development of non-specific physiological reactions (the general adaptation 
syndrome) to chronic comparatively intensive stresses. It describes the process 
of time-dependent depletion of the compensatory body reserve and the probability 
of regulation disorders and disruption of the adaptation to single factors or 
their combinations. On the population level, health risks predicted with the 
model are growth of death probability within a year and in a delayed period 
(transformation of age-specific coefficients of mortality) and a magnitude of 
reduction of remaining life expectancy.

